align=\"center\">0</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody></table><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-ascii\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/suppdata/apjab5a8bt1_ascii.txt?doi=10.3847/1538-4357/ab5a8b\" target=\"_blank\">ASCII</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/suppdata/apjab5a8bt1_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div><h3 id=\"apjab5a8bs3-1\" name=\"apjab5a8bs3-1\">3.1.\u00a0Magnitude Distribution</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf5\">5</a> shows distribution of F160W <em>H</em>-band magnitude for the RELICS high-redshift galaxies compared with that of the CLASH survey. In a given redshift and magnitude bin at relatively bright magnitudes (&lt;25 AB mag), RELICS and CLASH yield similar number densities of high-redshift galaxies. At fainter magnitudes, RELICS begins to suffer from incompleteness and photometric-redshift uncertainties (to be quantified in future work). Each RELICS WFC3/IR field consisted of 2 orbits and yielded 7 high-redshift candidates on average. Each CLASH WFC3/IR field was deeper, consisting of six orbits and yielding 14.5 high-redshift candidates on average (Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">2014</a>). Where CLASH had broader science goals requiring more orbits overall (524), RELICS was optimized to efficiently yield a large number of high-redshift candidates in fewer orbits (190). We note that our total high-redshift count is inflated by ~33% with respect to CLASH, given that we included candidates with high redshifts between the average of BPZ and EAZY (see Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bs2-2-3\">2.2.3</a>). Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf5\">5</a> also highlights the abundance of bright <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn14.gif\" alt=\"${m}_{\\mathrm{AB}}\\lt 26$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{m}_{\\mathrm{AB}}\\lt 26</script></span></span> candidates at a given redshift, which presents a promising sample for follow-up spectroscopy.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf5\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf5\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf5_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 5.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 5.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf5_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 5.</strong>\u00a0Distribution of WFC3 F160W <em>H</em>-band observed (lensed) magnitude for our <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, 7, and 8\u201310 RELICS samples in solid blue, left-hatched magenta, and right-hatched yellow histograms. The curves show the distribution of <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, 7, and 8\u201310 galaxies (blue, magenta, and yellow, respectively) from the first 18 clusters and 360 orbits of CLASH (Bradley et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">2014</a>). The above panel shows the photometric redshifts of individual RELICS galaxies as a function of their magnitude. RELICS produces a similar magnitude distribution of high-<em>z</em> galaxies as CLASH.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf5\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf5\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf5\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf5\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf6\">6</a> shows the <em>H</em>-band magnitude of the RELICS high-<em>z</em> candidates as a function of redshift compared with several large surveys including CANDELS (Bouwens et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib13\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib13\">2015</a>; Finkelstein et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib40\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib40\">2015</a>), the HFF (Ishigaki et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib52\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib52\">2018</a>), CLASH (Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">2014</a>), UltraVISTA (Bowler et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib19\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib19\">2017</a>), and BoRG/HIPPIES (Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib22\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib22\">2012</a>; Schmidt et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib92\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib92\">2014</a>; Calvi et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib28\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib28\">2016</a>). RELICS produces galaxies that are among the brightest at a given redshift over <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a05.5\u2013<em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a07.5, comparable to these much wider and deeper programs. We highlight this comparison to emphasize the efficiency of targeting strong lensing fields to produce high-<em>z</em> candidates, which is especially relevant as the costly overheads of <em>JWST</em> make the telescope more efficient at smaller area surveys.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf6\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf6\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf6_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 6.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 6.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf6_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 6.</strong>\u00a0<em>H</em>-band magnitude as a function of redshift. The high-<em>z</em> galaxy candidates from RELICS are shown as salmon-colored circles. Circles filled with an \"<em>X</em>\" mark candidates from the cluster field RXS 0603+42, which is at a low Galactic latitude (<em>b</em> \u2248 10\u00b0) and therefore has a potentially higher stellar contamination. The green squares are galaxies from CLASH (Bradley et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">2014</a>), the purple upward triangles from the Frontier Field (Ishigaki et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib52\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib52\">2018</a>), the red downward triangle from UltraVISTA (Bowler et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib19\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib19\">2017</a>), the blue diamonds from CANDELS (Bouwens et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib13\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib13\">2015</a>) (outlined diamonds are from the HUDF; see also Finkelstein et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib40\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib40\">2015</a>), and the orange pentagons from BoRG/HIPPIES (Bradley et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib22\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib22\">2012</a>; Schmidt et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib92\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib92\">2014</a>; Calvi et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib28\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib28\">2016</a>). Gray background lines follow the conversion from apparent magnitude to absolute UV magnitude. RELICS finds some of the brightest known galaxies at a given redshift over <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a08 to <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf6\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf6\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf6\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf6\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>Finally, Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf7\">7</a> displays the number density of galaxies in bins of magnitude over <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a06\u20138. We assume an area of 4.5 arcmin<sup>2</sup> for each of the 46 WFC3/IR pointings for a total survey area of 207 arcmin<sup>2</sup>. The actual area will change after lens models determine the magnification maps and the effective area covered for each cluster, although typical areas from CLASH range between 4.3 and 4.8 arcmin<sup>2</sup> per cluster field. Nevertheless, we observe a clear excess in number density at the <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 and 7 bright magnitudes compared with unlensed fields. We note that the drop off at fainter magnitudes (<em>m</em><sub>AB</sub> &gt; 26.5) is due to survey incompleteness.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf7\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf7\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf7_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 7.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 7.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf7_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 7.</strong>\u00a0Number density of galaxies per magnitude and redshift bin at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, 7, and 8. The observed number densities in the 41-cluster RELICS samples are shown as salmon-colored circles, with their 1<em>\u03c3</em> Poissonian uncertainties. The green squares are the observed number densities seen in CLASH by Bradley et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">2014</a>) and the blue diamonds are those seen in CANDELS by Bouwens et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib13\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib13\">2015</a>). The blue and red-dashed curves represent the double power-law and Schechter fits to a suite of published luminosity function results (Bradley et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib22\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib22\">2012</a>; Oesch et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib75\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib75\">2012</a>; McLure et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib71\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib71\">2013</a>; Bouwens et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib13\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib13\">2015</a>; Finkelstein et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib40\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib40\">2015</a>; Stefanon et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib103\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib103\">2017</a>; Ono et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib80\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib80\">2018</a>) from the literature (see Finkelstein <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib38\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib38\">2016</a>). The faint, capped error bars and open symbols show the number densities where faint-magnitude incompleteness begins to dominate. The purple curves represent the expected number densities from CLASH after simulating lensing effects on the Bouwens et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib13\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib13\">2015</a>) literature luminosity function. Compared with CLASH, RELICS yields similar number densities of <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 galaxies, extending to brighter lensed magnitudes (<span class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn15.gif\" alt=\"$H\\ {m}_{\\mathrm{AB}}\\lt 26$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">H\\ {m}_{\\mathrm{AB}}\\lt 26</script></span></span>). At <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a07 and 8, RELICS yields somewhat lower number densities.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf7\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf7\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf7\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf7\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>To provide a baseline comparison for our results, we make use of a LF with a double power-law fit to a comprehensive set of <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, 7, and 8 results from the literature. A double power law has been found to work well in representing the extreme bright-end shape of the UV LF (Bowler et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib17\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib17\">2014</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib18\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib18\">2015</a>; Stefanon et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib103\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib103\">2017</a>; Ono et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib80\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib80\">2018</a>). By comparing the bright end of our results from RELICS against that of a double-law LF, we aim to show that the number density boost from lensing we observe exceeds even the expectation from the double-law LF, which already exhibits a much larger number of sources than a LF with a Schechter (Schechter <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib89\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib89\">1976</a>) form. As a second baseline comparison for our results, we also show the expectations from the literature-averaged Schechter function results from Finkelstein (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib38\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib38\">2016</a>), which features fewer sources at the extreme bright end due the bright-end shape of the Schechter function, but overall is very similar at luminosities less than 2<em>L</em>*.</p><p>Next, we apply typical CLASH cluster-lensing magnifications to model how the number densities of the true LF appear under the effects of cluster lensing. We only show the effects of lensing on the double-law LF, but we note that forms of the LF produce a similar lensed shape. Comparing the lensed LF with the binned number densities of RELICS and CLASH, we find they agree with the prediction well at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, and that both surveys tend to underproduce from the expected number of sources at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a07 and 8. It is hard to speculate if this is due to an actual bright-end decline in number density at higher redshifts, as seen by Bowler et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib19\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib19\">2017</a>), until we conduct full completeness simulations and lens modeling of all 41 RELICS clusters and consider the effects of cosmic variance.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjab5a8bs3-2\" name=\"apjab5a8bs3-2\">3.2.\u00a0Exceptionally Bright Sources</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The RGB image stamps of the brightest 40 galaxy candidates from RELICS for <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 and 7, and all candidates for <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a08 are shown in Figures <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf8\">8</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf9\">9</a>, and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf10\">10</a>, respectively. In particular, we note the third brightest <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 candidate, MACS 0308-904, which has been clearly arced by the effects of lensing and is likely highly magnified. Not all highly magnified galaxies will also be arced, which makes it very difficult with the current data to distinguish between stellar contaminants and high-<em>z</em> galaxies among the brightest candidates. We have already attempted to remove stellar contaminants by a combination of <em>YJH</em> colors and stellarity (Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf2\">2</a> and Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bs2-3\">2.3</a>). In addition, we checked the brightest candidates in our samples with the Galactic latitude of their cluster field. We find that \u22486 of our brightest <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 candidates come from a cluster field with relatively low Galactic latitude (RXS 0603+42, at <em>b</em> = 9<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/fdg.gif\" alt=\"fdg\" align=\"baseline\" />7). We specially note these objects in Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf6\">6</a> and their images and SEDs can be inspected in Figures <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf8\">8</a> and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf11\">11</a>. Besides this one cluster, we see no correlation between the number or brightness of high-<em>z</em> candidates and the Galactic latitude of the cluster fields. We anticipate a deeper exploration of contaminants in the future using lensing magnifications, <em>Spitzer</em> photometry, and/or spectroscopic redshifts.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf8\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf8\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf8_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 8.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 8.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf8_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 8.</strong>\u00a0Brightest 40 galaxy candidates from the <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 RELICS sample. Each RGB color image stamp is 5''\u00a0<b>&#x00d7;</b>\u00a05'' with the red channel as the sum of all IR bands, the G channel as the ACS F814W band, and the B channel the sum of ACS F435W and F606W. The F160W <em>H</em>-band AB magnitude is shown within each stamp, along with the adopted redshift (see Section <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bs2-3\">2.3</a>). The cluster name and catalog ID are shown at the top of each stamp.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf8\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf8\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf8\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf8\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf9\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf9\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf9_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 9.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 9.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf9_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 9.</strong>\u00a0Same as Figure <a href=\"#apjab5a8bf8\">8</a>, but for the brightest 40 objects from the <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a07 sample.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf9\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf9\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf9\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf9\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf10\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf10\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf10_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 10.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 10.</strong>\u00a0All galaxy candidates from the <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a08 RELICS sample. Each RGB color image stamp is 5''\u00a0<b>&#x00d7;</b>\u00a05'' with the red channel as the sum of all IR bands, the G channel as the ACS F814W band, and the B channel the sum of ACS F435W and F606W. The F160W <em>H</em>-band AB magnitude is shown within each stamp, along with the the adopted redshift (see Section <a class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bs2-3\">2.3</a>). The cluster name and catalog ID are shown at the top of each stamp.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf10\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf10\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf10\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf10\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>Following the same plotting grid of the image stamp figures, the SEDs of the brightest candidates and their photometric-redshift template fits for BPZ and EAZY are shown in Figures <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf11\">11</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf12\">12</a>, and <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf13\">13</a>, respectively. Several objects appear to have red SEDs, but we caution that this is because the rest-frame optical is unconstrained prior to the inclusion of <em>Spitzer</em>, which makes estimates of physical parameters like stellar mass unreliable. In Tables <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bt2\">2</a>\u2013<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bt4\">4</a> we make available the <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a06, 7, and 8 candidate galaxies from the RELICS survey. We include both the photometric estimates of EAZY and BPZ. The full table is available in machine readable format.</p><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjab5a8bt2\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table ancillary <em>HST</em> data and all the other redshift candidates, is available in a single machine readable table and at <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"webref\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://relics.stsci.edu/high-z\">http://relics.stsci.edu/high-z</a>. The 40 candidates brightest in F160W are shown here as an example of the format. All magnitudes are given as observed (lensed) isophotal AB magnitudes.</p>\n<a name=\"apjab5a8bt2fna\" id=\"apjab5a8bt2fna\"></a><sup> a</sup>The online tables use the full cluster name and ID as used by the released RELICS photometric catalogs.\n<a name=\"apjab5a8bt2fnb\" id=\"apjab5a8bt2fnb\"></a><sup> b</sup>The photometric redshift quoted here is the average of the EAZY and BPZ estimates, unless they differ by more than 1, in which case we adopt the higher redshift solution. Quoted redshift ranges [given in brackets] conservatively span the 95% confidence intervals from both methods.\n\n\n\n<p>Only a portion of this table is shown here to demonstrate its form and content. The 40 candidates brightest in F160W are shown here as an example of the format. All magnitudes are given as observed (lensed) isophotal AB magnitudes.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Only a portion of this table is shown here to demonstrate its form and content. A <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"webref\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/suppdata/apjab5a8bt3_mrt.txt\">machine-readable</a> version of the full table is available.</p>\n\n\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-table-data\" ancillary <em>HST</em> data and all the other redshift candidates, is available in a single machine readable table and at <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"webref\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"http://relics.stsci.edu/high-z\">http://relics.stsci.edu/high-z</a>. All magnitudes are given as observed (lensed) isophotal AB magnitudes.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Only a portion of this table is shown here to demonstrate its form and content. A <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"webref\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/suppdata/apjab5a8bt4_mrt.txt\">machine-readable</a> version of the full table is available.</p>\n\n\n</small></p><p class=\"franklin fs-16\">\n\t\t\tDownload table as:\u00a0\n            <span class=\"btn-multi-block\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-table-data\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/suppdata/apjab5a8bt4_mrt.txt\" target=\"_blank\">Data</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary wd-jnl-art-btn-typeset typeset-table-img\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/suppdata/apjab5a8bt4_lr.gif\" target=\"_blank\">Typeset image</a></span></p></div></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjab5a8bs4\" name=\"apjab5a8bs4\">4.\u00a0Conclusions</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>We present the candidate high-<em>z</em> galaxies first estimated from RELICS, an <em>HST</em> Treasury Program observing 41 galaxy clusters. We use two independent photometric-redshift fitting codes to determine the redshifts of each galaxy. We also compare the colors of the candidates to those of known dwarf stars, and apply a color selection to remove the most likely contaminants. Furthermore, we conduct a visual inspection of all potential high-<em>z</em> candidates, cleaning the sample of diffraction spikes, misidentified parts of larger galaxies, stars, spurious noise close to the infrared detector edge, transients between epochs, and other image artifacts.</p><p>The final sample of candidate high-<em>z</em> galaxies is of comparable size to the CLASH program, despite being significantly more shallow. In particular, we identify several candidates that are among the brightest galaxies at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06\u20138, as compared with much deeper and wider area surveys. This presents a promising sample for follow-up spectroscopy to study the nebular ionization conditions, Ly<em>\u03b1</em> emission, and other galaxy properties into the epoch of reionization.</p><p>Finally, we compare the number of galaxies found with the predictions from lensed LFs. We find that our <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 sample agrees with expectations from the literature LFs, while <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a07 and 8 begin to underproduce the number of candidates compared with expectations from current LFs. The paucity of galaxies from the higher redshift samples could imply the start of an accelerated bright-end evolution in the UV LF, although we await the completion of the <em>Spitzer</em> data and completeness simulations for further confirmation.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf11\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf11\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf11_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 11.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 11.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf11_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 11.</strong>\u00a0Best-fit SEDs from EAZY (red) and BPZ (blue) for the 50 brightest galaxy candidates from the <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06 RELICS sample. The diamonds and squares show the expected fluxes from the model SED for EAZY and BPZ respectively, and the green circles are the RELICS data. The typical photometric uncertainties are about the size of the data points. The top title shows the cluster and catalog ID number of each high-<em>z</em> candidate. ACS was developed under NASA contract NAS 5-32864. The <em>Spitzer Space Telescope</em> is operated by the Jet Propulsion Laboratory, California Institute of Technology under a contract with NASA. These observations are associated with program GO-14096. Archival data are associated with programs GO-9270, GO-12166, GO-12477, and GO-12253. Some of the data presented in this paper were obtained from the Mikulski Archive for Space Telescopes (MAST). This research made use of Photutils, an Astropy package for detection and photometry of astronomical sources (Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib20\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib20\">2019</a>). We are loading this command straight away, before the body loads, so that IF a user has JS enabled, their show hide panels will automatically be closed. */\n\t\t/* If this isn't here, then these panels appear open while the page is loading, then when the js loads at the bottom of the page, they are shut. Not nice */\n\t\tdocument.write(\"<style>.reveal-content{display:none;}.search-res-filter .reveal-content{display:block;}</style>\");\n\t\t}\n\t\t</script>\n\t\t<script>var __uzdbm_1 = \"8211a71a-786b-41c8-93ad-0fd33bfd5180\";var __uzdbm_2 = \"ZjhhNmRlZGEtODQyNy00Y2U1LWEwNzMtZTRjODA0YjcyYTllJDE1NS4xMDEuMjYuMTEx\";</script> <script>(function(w, d, e, u, c, g, a, b){ w[\"SSJSConnectorObj\"] = {ss_cid : c, domain_info: \"auto\"}; a = d.createElement(e); a.async = true; a.src = u; b = d.getElementsByTagName(e)[0]; b.parentNode.insertBefore(a, b); })(window,document,\"script\",\"https://cdn.perfdrive.com/aperture/aperture.js\",\"a1c3\",\"ssConf\");</script></head>\n\t<body itemscope itemtype=\"http://schema.org/Organization\" class=\"issn-0004-637X\">\n    <a id=\"back-to-top-target\" tabindex=\"-1\"></a>\n    <!-- Google Tag Manager (noscript) -->\n<noscript><iframe src=\"https://www.googletagmanager.com/ns.html?id=GTM-M73Z4W\"\n    height=\"0\" width=\"0\" style=\"display:none;visibility:hidden\"></iframe></noscript>\n<!-- End Google Tag Manager (noscript) --><div class=\"cookies-banner-wrap\" id=\"cookieBanner\">\n    <div class=\"cookies-banner cf\">\n        This site uses cookies. <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The American Astronomical Society (AAS), established in 1899 and based in Washington, DC, is the major organization of professional astronomers in North America. Its membership of about 7,000 individuals also includes physicists, mathematicians, geologists, engineers, and others whose research and educational interests lie within the broad spectrum of subjects comprising contemporary astronomy. The mission of the AAS is to enhance and share humanity's scientific understanding of the universe.</p> <p><a href=\"https://aas.org/\">https://aas.org/</a></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<!-- Partner logo tile starts -->\n<a href=\"\" class=\"overlay-launch\">\n    <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n</a>\n<span class=\"overlay-set\">\n    <div class=\"tint-screen\"></div>\n    <div class=\"overlay-panel\">\n        <a title=\"Close\"  class=\"close-icon close-overlay\" tabindex=\"0\" role=\"button\" aria-describedby=\"close-icon-description\"><span class=\"icon-close\"></span></a>\n        <p id=\"close-icon-description\" class=\"offscreen-hidden\">Click here to close this overlay, or press the \"Escape\" key on your keyboard.</p>\n        <div class=\"overlay-img\">\n            <a href=\"\">\n                <img border=\"0\" src=\"https://cms.iopscience.org/7ebd1b32-0439-11e9-b401-cfe9679c40e3/iop-2016.png?guest=true\" alt=\"The Institute of Physics, find out more\">\n            </a>\n        </div>\n        <div class=\"overlay-text\">\n            <p>The Institute of Physics (IOP) is a leading scientific society promoting physics and bringing physicists together for the benefit of all. It has a worldwide membership of around 50 000 comprising physicists from all sectors, as well as those with an interest in physics. It works to advance physics research, application and education; and engages with policy makers and the public to develop awareness and understanding of physics. Its publishing company, IOP Publishing, is a world leader in professional scientific communications.</p> <p><a href=\"https://www.iop.org\">https://www.iop.org</a></p></div>\n        <p class=\"ta-c mt-1 mb-2\"><a href=\"\"></a></p>\n    </div>\n</span>\n<!-- Partner logo tile ends -->\n\n<p></p>\n                </div>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n<!-- Branded journal header ends -->\n</div> <span class=\"icon-newtab\">\n            </a></p>\n        </div>\n\n    <!-- End Email Alert -->\n<!-- End Email Alert --><!-- Start Citation Alert Link -->\n                        <p>\n<div class=\"jnl-notifications-wrapper\">\n    <a class=\"wd-jnl-email-alert\" href=\"https://myiopscience.iop.org/signin?origin=a0&return=https%3A%2F%2Fiopscience.iop.org%2Fmyiopscience%2Falerts%2Fsubscribe%3FarticleID%3D0004-637X%2F889%2F2%2F189\"><span\n            class=\"icon-alarm icon-alarm--jhp\"></span>Create citation alert</a>\n</div><!-- End Citation Alert Link -->\n                    </div>\n\t\t</div>\n    </div>\n    <!-- Article information ends -->\n<!-- Start Info top-->\n    <!-- end Info top --><div class=\"article-content\">\n\t<span id=\"articleId\" class=\"hide\">0004-637X/889/2/189</span>\n<!-- Start Abstract -->\n    <h2 id=\"artAbst\" class=\"collapse-blocked\">Abstract</h2>\n        <!-- Start article video abstract -->\n\t<!-- End article video abstract -->\n\t<div class=\"article-text wd-jnl-art-abstract cf\" itemprop=\"description\">\n             <P>Massive foreground galaxy clusters magnify and distort the light of objects behind them, permitting a view into both the extremely distant and intrinsically faint galaxy populations. We present here the <IMG ALIGN=\"MIDDLE\" alt=\"$z\\sim 6\\mbox{--}8$\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/apjab5a8bieqn1.gif\"></IMG> candidate high-redshift galaxies from the Reionization Lensing Cluster Survey (RELICS), a <I>Hubble</I> and <I>Spitzer Space Telescope</I> survey of 41 massive galaxy clusters spanning an area of \u2248200\u00a0arcmin<SUP>2</SUP>. These clusters were selected to be excellent lenses, and we find similar high-redshift sample sizes and magnitude distributions as the Cluster Lensing And Supernova survey with <I>Hubble</I> (CLASH). We discover 257, 57, and eight candidate galaxies at <I>z</I>\u00a0~\u00a06, 7, and 8 respectively, (322 in total). The observed (lensed) magnitudes of the <I>z</I>\u00a0~\u00a06 candidates are as bright as AB mag ~23, making them among the brightest known at these redshifts, comparable with discoveries from much wider, blank-field surveys. RELICS demonstrates the efficiency of using strong gravitational lenses to produce high-redshift samples in the epoch of reionization. These brightly observed galaxies are excellent targets for follow-up study with current and future observatories, including the <I>James Webb Space Telescope</I>.</P> </div>\n    <!-- End abstract -->\n<!-- Start Export citation and abstract tools -->\n\t<p>\n\t\t<small>Export citation and abstract</small>\n\t\t<span class=\"btn-multi-block\">\n\t\t\t<a title=\"Export BibTex\">BibTeX</a>\n\t\t\t<a href=\"/export?articleId=0004-637X/889/2/189&doi=10.3847/1538-4357/ab5a8b&exportFormat=iopexport_ris&exportType=abs&navsubmit=Export+abstract\" class=\"btn btn-primary wd-btn-cit-abs-ris\" title=\"Export RIS\">RIS</a>\n\t\t</span>\n\t</p>\n<!-- End Export citation and abstract tools -->\n<!-- Start AAS Related Links -->\n<div class=\"reveal-container
