related links\">Related links</a>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"reveal-content\">\n    <div class=\"article-meta\"> \n      <ul>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2020ApJ...889..189S\" target=\"_blank\">NASA ADS Record <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://nedwww.ipac.caltech.edu/cgi-bin/nph-objsearch?refcode=2020ApJ...889..189S&search_type=Search \" target=\"_blank\">NED Objects <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"http://simbad.u-strasbg.fr/simbad/sim-ref?querymethod=bib&simbo=on&bibcode=2020ApJ...889..189S\" target=\"_blank\">Simbad Objects <span class=\"icon-newtab\"></span></a></li>\n      \t<li><a href=\"/journal/0004-637X/page/About%20Related%20Links\" target=\"_blank\">About Related Links</a></li>\n      \t</ul>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n</div>\n<!-- Start info bottom -->\n    <!-- End info bottom -->\n<!-- Start article full text -->\n\t<div xmlns:book=\"http://api.iop.org/Book/1.0/\" itemprop=\"articleBody\" class=\"wd-jnl-art-full-text article-text\">\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjab5a8bs1\" name=\"apjab5a8bs1\">1.\u00a0Introduction</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Images from modern extragalactic surveys are rich with red sources as we push deeper to reveal the faint, redshifted population of the very first galaxies. Our investment in this early epoch is for good reason; the first billion years of the universe (<em>t</em><sub>universe</sub> \u2248 1 Gyr at <em>z</em> = 5.5) cover an era of rapid evolution by both the first stars and the first galaxies (for a complete review, see Stark <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib97\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib97\">2016</a>). Moreover, this period spans the time when the universe underwent a phase transition from having primarily neutral hydrogen to primarily ionized hydrogen, a process called reionization. Understanding the properties and the relative number of intrinsically faint and intrinsically bright galaxies at this epoch directly affects our interpretation of how reionization occurred, given that the most likely culprits for reionization were intrinsically faint galaxies at <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a06 (Madau et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib64\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib64\">1999</a>; Yan et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib114\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib114\">2003</a>; Bunker et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib27\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib27\">2004</a>; Oesch et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib78\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib78\">2009</a>; Finkelstein et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib39\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib39\">2012</a>; Kuhlen &amp; Faucher-Gigu\u00e8re <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib58\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib58\">2012</a>; McLure et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib71\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib71\">2013</a>; Schmidt et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib92\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib92\">2014</a>; Atek et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib3\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib3\">2015a</a>; Ishigaki et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib51\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib51\">2015</a>; Robertson et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib88\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib88\">2015</a>; Matthee et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib68\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib68\">2017</a>; Lam et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib59\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib59\">2019</a>).</p><p>There have been a variety of approaches to reach this distant galaxy population. While more costly, deep and wide space-based, \"blank-field\" surveys such as the Cosmic Assembly Deep Extragalactic Legacy Survey (CANDELS; Grogin et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib44\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib44\">2011</a>; Koekemoer et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib56\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib56\">2011</a>) and the Hubble Ultra Deep Field (HUDF; Beckwith et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib6\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib6\">2006</a>; Bouwens et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib12\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib12\">2011</a>; Ellis et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib36\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib36\">2013</a>; Illingworth et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib50\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib50\">2013</a>; Koekemoer et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib55\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib55\">2013</a>) and Brightest of Reionization Galaxies (BoRG; Trenti et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib106\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib106\">2011</a>; Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib22\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib22\">2012</a>; Livermore et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib61\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib61\">2018</a>) Survey have produced exquisite data sets that have become a reference data set for high-redshift galaxies. The same approach with ground-based surveys, such as UltraVista (Scoville et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib93\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib93\">2007</a>; McCracken et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib69\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib69\">2012</a>; Bowler et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib16\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib16\">2012</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib19\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib19\">2017</a>), have similarly produced copious numbers of intrinsically bright high-<em>z</em> galaxies. Similarly, thousands of bright galaxies at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a06\u20137 were found in the Great Optically Luminous Dropout Research Using Subaru HSC (GOLDRUSH; Harikane et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib45\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib45\">2018</a>; Ono et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib80\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib80\">2018</a>) and the Systematic Identification of LAEs for Visible Exploration and Reionization Research Using Subaru HSC (SILVERRUSH; Konno et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib57\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib57\">2018</a>; Ouchi et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib81\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib81\">2018</a>; Shibuya et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib95\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib95\">2018a</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib96\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib96\">2018b</a>) surveys, confirming the low-<em>z</em> relation that galaxies with high equivalent width from rest-ultraviolet (UV) nebular lines, including Ly<em>\u03b1</em> 1216\u00a0\u00c5, are also metal poor and faint in their rest-UV continuum. This approach of searching deep or wide on \"blank fields\" has proven lucrative and has lead to the discovery of the inexplicably bright, most distant confirmed galaxy found to date at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a011.1 (<em>t</em><sub>universe</sub> \u2248 400 Myr; Oesch et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib77\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib77\">2016</a>).</p><p>Another approach is to take advantage of natural telescopes by observing strong gravitational lenses. Cluster-lensing surveys such as the Cluster Lensing and Supernovae Survey with Hubble (CLASH; Postman et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib85\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib85\">2012</a>; Zheng et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib115\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib115\">2012</a>; Coe et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib33\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib33\">2013</a>; Bouwens et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib11\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib11\">2014</a>; Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">2014</a>) and the Hubble Frontier Fields (HFF; Atek et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib5\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib5\">2015b</a>; Coe et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib31\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib31\">2015</a>; Lotz et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib62\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib62\">2017</a>; Ishigaki et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib52\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib52\">2018</a>) have produced most of the <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2265\u00a08 galaxy candidates and allowed us to make the first inferences of the star formation rate density at <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a09\u201310 (Zitrin et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib117\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib117\">2014</a>; Oesch et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib76\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib76\">2015</a>). Moreover, the magnifications produced by lensing enables us to reach intrinsically faint, low-mass galaxies. Thanks to carefully calibrated lensing models (e.g., Meneghetti et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib72\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib72\">2017</a>), subtraction of intracluster light (Merlin et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib73\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib73\">2016</a>; Livermore et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib60\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib60\">2017</a>), and calibration of the measured sizes (Kawamata et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib54\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib54\">2015</a>; Bouwens et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib14\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib14\">2017a</a>), there has been substantial progress in deriving both the prevalence of intrinsically faint, lower-luminosity galaxies and the faint-end slope of the ultraviolet (UV) luminosity function (LF; Atek et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib4\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib4\">2014</a>; Alavi et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib1\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib1\">2016</a>; Bouwens et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib15\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib15\">2017b</a>).</p><p>In addition, it is important to find highly magnified galaxies to detect intrinsically faint UV metal lines, such as C <span class=\"small-caps\">iv</span> <em>\u03bb</em>1548\u00a0\u00c5 (Stark et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib101\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib101\">2014</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib102\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib102\">2015b</a>) and C <span class=\"small-caps\">iii</span>] <em>\u03bb</em>1909\u00a0\u00c5 (Rigby et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib87\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib87\">2015</a>; Stark et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib100\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib100\">2015a</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib98\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib98\">2017</a>; Mainali et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib65\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib65\">2017</a>) at high redshift. These UV lines can now be seen out to <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a06\u20137, including intrinsically faint Ly<em>\u03b1</em> (Hoag et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib48\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib48\">2017</a>; Hashimoto et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib46\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib46\">2018</a>). It is imperative to detect these faint metal lines not only because they help us to deduce the shape of the ionizing spectra, but they also allow us to spectroscopically confirm the redshifts of galaxies in the epoch of reionization, given that the Ly<em>\u03b1</em> line becomes completely opaque to the line-of-site neutral intergalactic medium (Stark et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib99\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib99\">2010</a>; Schenker et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib90\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib90\">2012</a>; Tilvi et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib104\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib104\">2013</a>; Pentericci et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib82\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib82\">2014</a>).</p><p>The rich history of using strong lensing systems to study in detail <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2248\u00a04\u20137 galaxies (Franx et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib42\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib42\">1997</a>; Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib21\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib21\">2008</a>; Zitrin et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib116\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib116\">2012</a>; Jones et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib53\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib53\">2013</a>) and reveal the <em>z</em>\u00a0\u2248\u00a08\u201311 population (Zheng et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib115\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib115\">2012</a>; Bouwens et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib11\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib11\">2014</a>; Zitrin et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib117\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib117\">2014</a>; McLeod et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib70\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib70\">2016</a>; Ishigaki et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib52\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib52\">2018</a>) was the motivation for the Reionization Lensing Cluster Survey (RELICS; Coe et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib32\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib32\">2019</a>). RELICS is a 190-orbit <em>Hubble Space Telescope</em> (<em>HST</em>) Treasury Program designed to build off of the success of other <em>HST</em> lensing surveys like CLASH and the HFF, and take advantage of clusters with existing <em>HST</em>/ACS imaging and/or data suggesting exceptionally high cluster masses. In short, the survey targeted 41 massive galaxy clusters selected by the <em>Planck</em> survey (Planck Collaboration et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib84\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib84\">2016</a>) to be excellent lensing systems. This survey is timely in advance of the <em>James Webb Space Telescope</em> (<em>JWST</em>) launch date, as <em>JWST</em> was not designed to be a wide-field survey telescope and will benefit from existing high-redshift candidates. We present here the first results of the RELICS program [<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"dataset\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://doi.org/10.17909/T9SP45\" data-art-data-content-type=\"External repository\" data-toolbar-link=\"https://doi.org/10.17909/T9SP45\" data-toolbar-title=\"MAST dataset\" data-art-data-type=\"ext-rep-mast\" id=\"https://doi.org/10.17909/T9SP45\">10.17909/T9SP45</a> ], providing to the community all of its high-redshift candidates found to date.</p><p>This paper is organized as follows. In Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bs2\">2</a>, we summarize our observations, redshifts, and selection. In Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bs3\">3</a>, we describe our resulting magnitudes of the objects in our sample, and present the spectral energy distributions (SEDs) and images of bright sources. In Section <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"secref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bs4\">4</a>, we discuss our conclusions and future work. Throughout, we assume concordance cosmology using <em>H</em><sub>0</sub>\u00a0= 70 km s<sup>\u22121</sup> Mpc<sup>\u22121</sup>, <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn2.gif\" alt=\"${{\\rm{\\Omega }}}_{{\\rm{M}},0}=0.3$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{{\\rm{\\Omega }}}_{{\\rm{M}},0}=0.3</script></span></span> and \u03a9<sub>\u039b,0</sub>\u00a0=\u00a00.7. All magnitudes quoted here are measured with respect to the AB system, <em>m</em><sub>AB</sub>\u00a0= 31.4\u20132.5 log(<em>f</em><sub><em>\u03bd</em></sub>/1 nJy) (Oke &amp; Gunn <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib79\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib79\">1983</a>).</p></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjab5a8bs2\" name=\"apjab5a8bs2\">2.\u00a0Data, Redshifts, and Sample Selection</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><h3 id=\"apjab5a8bs2-1\" name=\"apjab5a8bs2-1\">2.1.\u00a0RELICS Cluster Selection and <em>HST</em> Photometry</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The full details of the selection criteria for the RELICS cluster fields are described by Coe et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib32\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib32\">2019</a>). In short, the clusters were selected by a combination of their cluster mass and preexisting ACS imaging. From the most massive Planck clusters (identified by their Sunyaev Zel'dovich cluster mass; Planck Collaboration et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib84\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib84\">2016</a>), we first selected the eight most massive clusters that had <em>HST</em>/ACS but not WFC3 infrared imaging, and another 13 massive Planck clusters that had no <em>HST</em> or <em>Spitzer</em> imaging at all. The 20 other RELICS clusters are selected from known strong lenses that already have <em>HST</em> optical imaging. We also note that seven of the RELICS clusters can be found in the MACS program by Ebeling et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib35\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib35\">2001</a>). We initially inferred the cluster-lensing strengths from a variety of sources, including their X-ray mass (MCXC; Mantz et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib66\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib66\">2010</a>; Piffaretti et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib83\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib83\">2011</a>), weak lensing mass (Applegate et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib2\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib2\">2014</a>; Umetsu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib107\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib107\">2014</a>; von der Linden et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib110\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib110\">2014</a>; Hoekstra et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib49\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib49\">2015</a>; Sereno <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib94\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib94\">2015</a>), Sloan Digital Sky Survey data (Wen et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib111\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib111\">2012</a>; Wong et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib112\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib112\">2013</a>), and other SZ mass estimates (Hasselfield et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib47\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib47\">2013</a>; Bleem et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib10\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib10\">2015</a>). Further details on the cluster selection can be found in Cerny et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib29\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib29\">2017</a>) and Coe et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib32\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib32\">2019</a>).</p><p>We target all 41 clusters with two orbits of WFC3/IR comprising observations in F105W, F125W, F140W, and F160W. Five clusters are observed with an additional pointing, for a total of 46 IR fields. We take advantage of existing archival ACS imaging, and for the 18 clusters without any F435W, F606W, and F814W we observe three orbits total, with one orbit per filter. For the ACS imaging, we also observe WFC3/IR fields in parallel, which are not explored in this work. The observations are split into two epochs separated by about a month to facilitate variability search. Twenty additional orbits were allocated for variability target of opportunity follow-up.</p><p>The SExtractor (version 2.8.6; Bertin &amp; Arnouts <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib9\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib9\">1996</a>) object selection and <em>HST</em> photometry are described by Coe et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib32\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib32\">2019</a>), which we summarize here. First, we use the AstroDrizzle package (Gonzaga et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib43\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib43\">2012</a>) to combine all subexposures from each filter. After aligning the filters to the same pixel frame, we correct the absolute astrometry with the <em>Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer</em> point-source catalog (Wright et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib113\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib113\">2010</a>). Then, we construct the final drizzled images by sampling the point-spread functions of both the ACS and WFC3/IR cameras in 30 milli-arcsecond (mas) pixel<sup>\u22121</sup> and 60 mas pixel<sup>\u22121</sup> scales.</p><p>Finally, RELICS produces the full photometric catalogs of each cluster field. In this work, we use the catalogs based on a detection image comprised of the 60 mas weighted stack of all WFC3/IR imaging. The source extraction was performed with SExtractor in dual-image mode, with fluxes measured within the isophotal apertures. All fluxes are corrected for Galactic extinction, assuming the extinction law by Schlafly &amp; Finkbeiner (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib91\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib91\">2011</a>). We find nominal 5<em>\u03c3</em> depths of 27.1\u201327.6 AB mag for the ACS filters and 26.0\u201326.6 AB mag for the WFC3/IR filters.</p></div><h3 id=\"apjab5a8bs2-2\" name=\"apjab5a8bs2-2\">2.2.\u00a0Photometric Redshifts</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>In general, photometric-redshift codes use input photometric bands to identify a sharp change in flux between two wavelengths and, by leveraging with data at other wavelengths, infer the presence of the Lyman break (caused by the line-of-sight neutral intergalactic medium absorbing photons at rest wavelengths shorter than 1216 \u00c5), the Balmer break (a feature more pronounced in older stellar populations), or strong nebular emission lines. The main difference between photometric redshifts and other selection methods, such as color and magnitude limits, is that the former is able to assign a likelihood to each redshift by fitting the observed photometry to synthetic photometry from a library of redshifted stellar population templates.</p><p>In this work, we use two independent photometric-redshift fitting codes to identify high-<em>z</em> galaxy candidates: the Bayesian photometric-redshift code (BPZ v1.99.3; Ben\u00edtez <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib7\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib7\">2000</a>; Ben\u00edtez et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib8\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib8\">2004</a>; Coe et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib30\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib30\">2006</a>) and the Easy and Accurate Z (photometric redshifts) from Yale (EAZY; Brammer et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib24\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib24\">2008</a>). Both are similar in that they fit a variety of empirically driven galaxy SEDs to the data and find the template and redshift that best represents the object. While these codes have been extensively compared for blank-field galaxies at lower redshifts (<em>z</em> &lt; 6; Brinchmann et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib25\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib25\">2017</a>), in this work we explored their differences for galaxies in lensing fields at higher redshifts. Besides the choice of template SEDs, perhaps the biggest difference between BPZ and EAZY is the handling of the magnitude prior. In BPZ, the Bayesian prior <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn3.gif\" alt=\"$P(z,t| {m}_{0})$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">P(z,t| {m}_{0})</script></span></span> is a redshift and magnitude (<em>m</em><sub>0</sub>)-dependent prior applied to each template <em>t</em>, so as to down-weight the likelihood of, for example, the unphysical presence of bright elliptical galaxies at very high (<em>z</em> &gt; 4) redshifts. Similarly, EAZY weights the <em>P</em>(<em>z</em>) with a template-dependent <em>K</em>-band luminosity prior. In the following sections, we present our assumptions for each fitting code and use of priors.</p><h4 id=\"apjab5a8bs2-2-1\" name=\"apjab5a8bs2-2-1\">2.2.1.\u00a0BPZ Redshifts</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>BPZ compares the observed RELICS fluxes with PEGASE (Fioc &amp; Rocca-Volmerange <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib41\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib41\">1997</a>) SED templates. BPZ employs a Madau (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib63\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib63\">1995</a>) intergalactic medium attenuation, which accentuates the Lyman break. The default templates span a range of rest-frame <em>UVJ</em> colors, and are combined to produce SEDs with synthetic spectra similar to the high-quality spectra of most galaxies (e.g., with \u22641% outliers; see Coe et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib33\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib33\">2013</a>), including red dusty star-forming galaxies. We use the default BPZ templates for fitting redshifts in this work.</p><p>We found that for BPZ some simple prior must be assumed to avoid an overpopulation of quiescent-like SEDs at high redshift. With this prior, we calculate the posterior <em>P</em>(<em>z</em>) for every object in each RELICS field and define our accepted BPZ redshifts as the redshift corresponding to the mode of the final probability function.</p><p>To test the reliability of our assumed prior for lensed galaxies, we conduct an input-output redshift simulation. For each BPZ template, we calculate their synthetic fluxes, apply Gaussian perturbations, and assign uncertainties based off of the average magnitude-dependent uncertainties of the RELICS data. We then redshift each template and assign a range of magnitudes, and run BPZ to test the recovery. We find that BPZ accurately recovers <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn4.gif\" alt=\"$5.5\\lt z\\lt 8.5$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">5.5\\lt z\\lt 8.5</script></span></span> galaxies at all magnitudes <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn5.gif\" alt=\"$27\\lt m\\lt 22$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">27\\lt m\\lt 22</script></span></span> with a 68% scatter in the recovery distribution of less than 0.2 from their true input redshifts. For elliptical/evolved galaxy SEDs, the recovery is less (0.4 &lt; <em>\u03c3</em> &lt; 0.6), and the outlier fraction increases with fainter elliptical galaxies. We conclude that the BPZ prior is not causing us to miss a substantial population of bright <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a05.5 galaxies.</p></div><h4 id=\"apjab5a8bs2-2-2\" name=\"apjab5a8bs2-2-2\">2.2.2.\u00a0EAZY Redshifts</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>Similar to BPZ, the EAZY photometric-redshift code creates the redshift likelihood density function (<em>P</em>(<em>z</em>)) by computing the <em>\u03c7</em><sup>2</sup> between the observed fluxes and a linear combination of redshifted empirical SED templates. EAZY includes 7 default templates from PEGASE stellar population models (Fioc &amp; Rocca-Volmerange <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib41\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib41\">1997</a>), a red, highly dust-obscured galaxy (Maraston <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib67\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib67\">2005</a>), and an extreme, high-equivalent width (EW) nebular emission line galaxy (Erb et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib37\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib37\">2010</a>).</p><p>Similar to our test with BPZ, we explore the reliability of the default EAZY prior for lensed galaxies at high redshift. We calculated synthetic fluxes from the EAZY templates, applied magnitude-dependent flux uncertainties that are similar to the RELICS data, and redshift them to 5.5\u00a0&lt;\u00a0<em>z</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a08.5. We found that the default prior has poor recovery and tends to systematically prefer the high-EW low-<em>z</em> solutions over the correct input high-<em>z</em> solutions. We therefore chose to adopt a flat prior for EAZY redshifts.</p></div><h4 id=\"apjab5a8bs2-2-3\" name=\"apjab5a8bs2-2-3\">2.2.3.\u00a0Redshift Designation</h4><div class=\"article-text\"><p>To construct our final sample of high-<em>z</em> galaxy candidates, we ultimately choose to adopt the average redshift between the BPZ and EAZY estimates. We accordingly propagate the redshift uncertainties of the two codes to find the final redshift uncertainty <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn6.gif\" alt=\"$\\sigma =0.5\\sqrt{{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{EAZY}}^{2}+{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{BPZ}}^{2}}$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">\\sigma =0.5\\sqrt{{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{EAZY}}^{2}+{\\sigma }_{\\mathrm{BPZ}}^{2}}</script></span></span>. When their redshifts differ by \u0394<em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a01, we adopt the code with the higher redshift solution and use its uncertainty.The two codes differ by a large amount for objects that have a degenerate low-redshift solution (<em>z</em> ~ 1\u20132) of a red, highly dust-obscured galaxy, or one with an evolved stellar population. A slight preference to one of these solutions, due to the different assumed templates, is the primary cause for the few cases where BPZ and EAZY redshifts differ by \u0394<em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a01 (see Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf1\">1</a>).</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf1\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf1\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf1_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 1.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 1.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf1_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 1.</strong>\u00a0Comparison of EAZY and BPZ photometric redshifts for our high-<em>z</em> sample. The gray regions show \u0394<em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a0\u00b11. Blue, magenta, and yellow represent our <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, 7, and 8 samples respectively. Objects with a high difference in redshift are due to one code preferring a <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a01\u20132 dusty or high EW nebular emission line galaxy. Redshifts from BPZ and EAZY closely agree for all bright (F160W &lt; 24.5) galaxies.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf1\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf1\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf1\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf1\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>We note that the redshifts of EAZY and BPZ agree for the brightest high-redshift candidates in RELICS (F160W &lt; 24.5 AB mag). However, the two codes differ for some of the fainter candidates. Had we adopted BPZ redshifts for our selection, our samples would be 75% the size of our fiducial sample. This makes sense because as we found above, BPZ has difficulty in identifying evolved, faint galaxies at <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a05.5. We aim to validate our sample further by a close inspection of the available <em>Spitzer</em> photometry and follow-up spectroscopy. In the next section, we describe the rest of our selection methods and visual inspection of each high-redshift galaxy candidate.</p></div></div><h3 id=\"apjab5a8bs2-3\" name=\"apjab5a8bs2-3\">2.3.\u00a0High-<em>z</em> Sample Selection</h3><div class=\"article-text\"><p>The RELICS catalogs contain a combined total of over 76,000 sources. From these sources, we identify 2425 objects with appreciable likelihood at <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a05.5, <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn7.gif\" alt=\"$P(z\\gt 5.5)\\gt 40 \\% $\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">P(z\\gt 5.5)\\gt 40 \\%</script></span></span>. After initial visual inspections, we found that galaxies only appeared to be bona fide candidates (that is, a signal-to-noise ratio &gt; 3, small sizes, and detections in individual infrared bands) if at least one of the photometric-redshift fitting codes had a median or peak likelihood at <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a05.5. This lead us to adopting a single redshift per object to produce a complete candidate list. We took advantage of our use of two independent photometric-redshift codes by assigning the redshift of each object to be the average of the BPZ and BPZ estimates unless they differ by \u0394<em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a01, in which case we adopted the higher redshift solution. We note that the BPZ and EAZY redshifts are in approximate agreement (<span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn8.gif\" alt=\"$| {\\rm{\\Delta }}z| \\lt 1$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">| {\\rm{\\Delta }}z| \\lt 1</script></span></span>) for 87% of the sample, and are in excellent agreement for the brightest sources (F160W\u00a0&lt;\u00a025.5). We then selected objects with <em>z</em><sub>phot</sub>\u00a0&gt;\u00a05.5 to reduce the initial candidate list to 1337 objects. We further refined the sample by selecting galaxies with an F160W detection greater than 3<em>\u03c3</em> as adopted by Bradley et <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">al.(2014</a>), reducing to 841 objects.</p><p>With any high-<em>z</em> sample, we must be diligent to remove contamination by foreground Galactic stars. L-, T-, and M-dwarf stars and brown dwarfs have similar broadband IR colors as <em>z</em>\u00a0=\u00a06\u20137 galaxies (Tilvi et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib104\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib104\">2013</a>). The SExtractor \"stellarity\" parameter is one potentially effective way of doing so, with generally effective discriminatory power to <em>J</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a025 or <em>J</em>\u00a0&lt;\u00a026 reported by Finkelstein et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib40\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib40\">2015</a>) and Bouwens et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib13\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib13\">2015</a>), respectively, but with lesser reliability fainter than these levels. This is exacerbated in lensing fields where high stellarity objects could be stars or strongly lensed high-<em>z</em> galaxies. To avoid these objects, we use both stellarity and a color selection to reduce our stellar contamination.</p><p>First, we outright remove objects with a stellarity \u22650.98 (111 objects) because these objects have very low FWHM (&lt;0<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcs.gif\" alt=\"farcs\" align=\"bottom\" />25) and magnitudes systematically brighter than expected for typical lensing magnifications (mean of F160W ~ 22.8 AB mag, well above the distribution of magnitudes of lensed <em>z</em> &gt; 6 galaxies from CLASH; see Bradley et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib23\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib23\">2014</a>). While our stellarity limit is higher than the one used by Oesch et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib75\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib75\">2012</a>) on blank fields, we note that the fields used in this work contain strong gravitational lenses capable of magnifying compact galaxies with high stellarity. Such high-<em>z</em> galaxies have been found by Bouwens et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib14\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib14\">2017a</a>) with very compact light profiles and physical sizes as small as &lt;50 pc (see also Vanzella et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib109\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib109\">2016</a>, <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib108\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib108\">2017</a>). In addition, recent spectroscopy of some of the high stellarity, extremely bright sources in our RELICS sample (in prep) reveal the SEDs of these objects better match starburst galaxies than known low-mass dwarf stars.</p><p>Second, we compare the <em>YJH</em> colors of the RELICS high-<em>z</em> sample with the colors of known L-, T-, and M-dwarf stars (Cushing et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib34\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib34\">2005</a>; Rayner et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib86\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib86\">2009</a>). Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf2\">2</a> shows that the colors of most objects at intermediate stellarity (stellarity of 0.80\u20130.98) are dissimilar to the colors of known L- and T-dwarf stars. Nevertheless, we make a selection to omit high-<em>z</em> candidates that satisfy both intermediate stellarity (80%\u201398%) and <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn9.gif\" alt=\"$(Y\\mbox{--}J)\\gt 0.45$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">(Y\\mbox{--}J)\\gt 0.45</script></span></span> colors, which removes 11 high-<em>z</em> candidates from our sample. We also note that there are on order \u224810 candidates with both intermediate stellarity and colors close to most M dwarfs, but the <em>YJH</em> colors or other available color combinations do not well distinguish M dwarfs from high-<em>z</em> galaxies. We estimate that there may be an M-dwarf contamination rate of ~5%\u201310%.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf2\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf2\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf2_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 2.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 2.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf2_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 2.</strong>\u00a0The YJH colors of the RELICS high-<em>z</em> galaxy candidates. The red circles and green squares are objects with <span class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn10.gif\" alt=\"${z}_{\\mathrm{phot},\\mathrm{Max}}\\gt 5.5$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{z}_{\\mathrm{phot},\\mathrm{Max}}\\gt 5.5</script></span></span>, where the latter are those with high stellarity (&gt;0.8). The blue diamonds and yellow stars are colors of known L &amp;T and M dwarfs respectively, taken from IRTF observed spectral library (Cushing et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib34\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib34\">2005</a>; Rayner et al. <a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib86\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib86\">2009</a>). Most of the high-redshift galaxy candidates with high stellarity (green squares) have colors dissimilar from the dwarf stars. We remove all objects with <span class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn11.gif\" alt=\"${z}_{\\mathrm{phot},\\mathrm{Max}}\\gt 5.5$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">{z}_{\\mathrm{phot},\\mathrm{Max}}\\gt 5.5</script></span></span>, <span class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn12.gif\" alt=\"$(Y-J)\\,\\gt 0.45$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">(Y-J)\\,\\gt 0.45</script></span></span>, and stellarity &gt;0.8, which correspond to the green squares in the blue shaded region.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf2\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf2\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf2\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf2\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>Finally, we conduct an extensive visual inspection of all remaining candidates to ensure no spurious artifacts entered the sample. The most common candidate that was removed by visual inspection was stellar diffraction spikes that were segmented into their own object by SExtractor. This is because the WFC3/IR diffraction spikes do not overlap with the ACS diffraction spikes, and thus they can appear as optical dropouts if SExtractor identified part of the spike as an individual object. The SEDs of these spikes are flat in <em>f</em><sub><em>\u03bd</em></sub> with a strong spectral break, very similar to a high-<em>z</em> galaxy. Other removed candidates included some that appeared very large in size (isophotal area &gt;100 pixels) and spherical in shape (not obviously stretched in one direction by lensing shear), indicative of foreground objects. These objects also had a significant low-<em>z</em> solution <span xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"inline-eqn\"><span class=\"tex\"><span class=\"texImage\"><img src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bieqn13.gif\" alt=\"$P(z\\lt 4)\\gt 40$\" align=\"top\"></img></span><script type=\"math/tex\">P(z\\lt 4)\\gt 40</script></span></span>%. Other removed objects were within the faint diffuse edges of a foreground elliptical galaxy, a result of SExtractor mistakenly identifying the noisy edge of a foreground galaxy as its own object. Similarly, sometimes the object was clearly an oversegmented part of another galaxy that SExtractor identified as its own object. Finally, the last class of removed objects were those that were visually identified as a noise artifact: all their signal was coming from a few pixels, typically with an isophotal area &lt;15 pixels. In summary we discover 257 candidate galaxies at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, 57 at ~7 and 8 at <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a08, for 322 galaxies in total.</p></div></div>\n<h2 class=\"header-anchor\" id=\"apjab5a8bs3\" name=\"apjab5a8bs3\">3.\u00a0Results</h2><div class=\"article-text\" data-mobile-collapse=\"\"><p>Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf3\">3</a> shows RGB color images of the top nine high-<em>z</em>-producing fields (excluding RXS 0603+42, whose two WFC3/IR pointings are separated by 6'), and the overlaid position of each high-<em>z</em> candidate. These images show that our candidate high-<em>z</em> galaxies are not clustered around the edges of the IR detector, thanks to our visual screening of every candidate. Cerny et al. (<a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib29\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib29\">2017</a>) conducted an analysis of the first five RELICS clusters, which span the range of masses and redshifts of the clusters in the full program. They found that these five clusters had lensing efficiencies of similar strength to the Frontier Fields. In future works, we will publish the lens models and magnifications of all 41 clusters, which will allow us to explore the lensed counter images.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf3\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf3\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf3_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 3.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 3.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf3_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 3.</strong>\u00a0Color images of the top nine clusters after rank ordering by the number of <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a05.5 galaxies they produce (excluding RXS 0603+42 whose two WFC3/IR pointings are separated by 6'). North is up, and east is to the left. The images are scaled to 3<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcm.gif\" alt=\"farcm\" align=\"baseline\" />25\u00a0<b>&#x00d7;</b>\u00a03<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcm.gif\" alt=\"farcm\" align=\"baseline\" />25, except for ACT 0102-49 which is 4<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcm.gif\" alt=\"farcm\" align=\"baseline\" />25\u00a0<b>&#x00d7;</b>\u00a04<img src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/icons/Entities/farcm.gif\" alt=\"farcm\" align=\"baseline\" />25. The cyan, magenta, and yellow circles mark the location of the <em>z</em>\u00a0~\u00a06, 7, and 8 candidate galaxies, respectively.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf3\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf3\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-hires-img-apjab5a8bf3\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadHRFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf3\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> High-resolution image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><p>The breakdown of the number of galaxies in each cluster and each redshift bin are shown in Table <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"tabref\" href=\"#apjab5a8bt1\">1</a>. Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf4\">4</a> displays these number counts per cluster as a histogram. Clearly, some clusters produce many more high-<em>z</em> candidates than others, even after accounting for the five clusters that have additional WFC3/IR pointings. For example, the top \u224812% of the high-<em>z</em> producing clusters contain as many candidates (almost a third of the entire <em>z</em> &gt; 5.5 sample) as the bottom 50% of the clusters. Figure <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" href=\"#apjab5a8bf4\">4</a> also shows that there appears to be little to no correlation between the ability of a cluster to produce high-<em>z</em> sources and its cluster mass, at least at these high masses. However, a weak correlation exists with the number of high-<em>z</em> candidates and the cluster redshift. However, there may be several reasons for why some clusters are better at producing high-<em>z</em> sources than others, such as a dependence on the cluster mass distribution and concentration, the latter of which is expected to correlate with dark matter halo mass (Bullock et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib26\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib26\">2001</a>; Neto et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib74\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib74\">2007</a>; Umetsu et al. <a xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib107\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib107\">2014</a>). In addition, there may be sample variance in the alignment of background galaxies. A comprehensive exploration of cluster-lensing strength will require a comparison between the lens models from all RELICS clusters.</p><figure xmlns:xlink=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink\" id=\"apjab5a8bf4\" tabindex=\"-1\" role=\"group\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\" data-toolbar-type=\"figure\" data-toolbar-link=\"apjab5a8bf4\" data-toolbar-img=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf4_lr.jpg\" data-toolbar-title=\"Figure 4.\"><figure><div class=\"panzoom-container\"><div class=\"panzoom-parent\" style=\"overflow: hidden; position: relative;\"><img class=\"panzoom\" alt=\"Figure 4.\" src=\"https://static.iopscience.com/2.44.0/img/lazy-loading-placeholder.gif\" data-src=\"https://cdn.iopscience.com/images/0004-637X/889/2/189/Full/apjab5a8bf4_lr.jpg\" style=\"transform: matrix(1, 0, 0, 1, 0, 0); backface-visibility: hidden; transform-origin: 50% 50% 0px; cursor: move; transition: transform 200ms ease-in-out 0s;\"></img></div><div class=\"buttons zoom-tools\"><button class=\"zoom-in\"><span class=\"icon-zoomin\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom In\n\t\t\t\t</button><button class=\"zoom-out\"><span class=\"icon-zoomout\"></span>\n\t                 Zoom Out\n\t\t\t\t</button><span class=\"mobile-block\"><button class=\"reset\"><span class=\"icon-loop\"></span>\n\t                     Reset image size\n\t\t\t\t\t</button></span></div></div><figcaption><div class=\"article-text figure-caption\"><p><strong>Figure 4.</strong>\u00a0Number of high-<em>z</em> candidates for each cluster field observed by RELICS. Top: histograms of the number of <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a05.5 candidate galaxies (solid blue and hatched red) and number of <em>z</em>\u00a0&gt;\u00a06.5 candidates (solid blue only). The five clusters with two WFC3/IR pointings are noted with the solid stars. Some clusters produce considerable numbers of high-<em>z</em> candidates compared with others. Bottom: the number of high-<em>z</em> candidates per cluster as a function of the cluster redshift. The blue-to-red colors portray the cluster mass (M<sub>500</sub>) from Planck Collaboration et al. (<a class=\"cite\" href=\"#apjab5a8bbib84\" id=\"fnref-apjab5a8bbib84\">2016</a>), where the crossed circles show the two clusters without mass estimates. There is a weak correlation between the cluster redshift and the ability of a cluster to lens high-<em>z</em> sources, and little correlation with the cluster mass.</p></div><p class=\"mb-05 print-hide\">Download figure:</p><span class=\"btn-multi-block print-hide\"><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-std-img\" id=\"wd-jnl-art-btn-std-img-apjab5a8bf4\" href=\"/0004-637X/889/2/189/downloadFigure/figure/apjab5a8bf4\"><span class=\"icon-image\"></span> Standard image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a><a class=\"btn btn-primary fig-dwnld-hi-img\" image\n\t\t\t\t\t</a></span></figcaption></figure></figure><div tabindex=\"-1\" id=\"apjab5a8bt1\" class=\"boxout boxout-bdr-grey keyboard-focus-only\"><p><b>Table 1.</b>\u00a0\nHigh-<em>z</em> Number
